{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01LGcbAhi5ndf9xgPDFr1my7","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→# Session Retrospective — 2026-03-21\n     2→\n     3→**Sprint:** Operational Excellence Sprint\n     4→**Session window:** ~04:21Z – ~04:45Z (approx 25 minutes)\n     5→**Sprint progress:** 15/20 stories done (75%), Epic 3 nearing completion\n     6→\n     7→---\n     8→\n     9→## 1. Session Summary\n    10→\n    11→| Story | Epic | Outcome | Phases Completed |\n    12→|-------|------|---------|-----------------|\n    13→| 3-3-onboard-alias | Epic 3: Audit Command | Verifying (all phases done, awaiting final verification) | create-story, dev-story, code-review |\n    14→\n    15→One story was attempted this session. It progressed through story creation, implementation, and code review without blocking failures. The story replaced a 478-line onboard command with a 40-line alias delegating to a shared audit handler — a 92% reduction in code.\n    16→\n    17→**Test results at session end:** 2783 tests passing across 119 files, 96.97% overall coverage, all files above 80% floor.\n    18→\n    19→---\n    20→\n    21→## 2. Issues Analysis\n    22→\n    23→### Bugs Discovered During Implementation\n    24→\n    25→- **Unsafe double type assertion** (HIGH) — `audit-action.ts:86` used `as unknown as Record<string, unknown>` to bypass TypeScript type safety. Fixed during code review by using spread operator instead.\n    26→- **Dead branch guard** (MEDIUM) — `audit-action.ts:101` had a `fixStories &&` check that was always true at that point. Simplified to `else`.\n    27→\n    28→### Workarounds Applied (Tech Debt Introduced)\n    29→\n    30→- **`console.log` in audit-action.ts:111** (LOW, not fixed) — The shared handler uses `console.log` directly instead of output utilities. Established codebase pattern but violates project conventions. Needs a new `raw()` output utility to fix properly. **Tracked as tech debt.**\n    31→- **`formatAuditJson()` is a pass-through no-op** (LOW, not fixed) — Exists for API symmetry with `formatAuditHuman()` but does nothing. Not harmful but adds a meaningless abstraction layer.\n    32→\n    33→### Code Quality Concerns\n    34→\n    35→- **NFR9 violation** — `onboard.test.ts` initially hit 325 lines (limit: 300). Compacted to 230 lines during code review. Shows that test file size estimates in story planning (100-150 lines) can be unreliable.\n    36→- **Branch coverage gap** — Missing test for `skipped: true` path in audit-action.ts. Added during code review, bringing branch coverage to 100%.\n    37→\n    38→### Verification Gaps\n    39→\n    40→- Story is in `verifying` status — final verification pass has not yet been completed as of session end.\n    41→\n    42→### Tooling/Infrastructure Problems\n    43→\n    44→- None reported this session.\n    45→\n    46→### Planning/Ambiguity Issues\n    47→\n    48→- **Ambiguous AC3** — Epic said `onboard scan` should map to \"equivalent audit subcommand\" but audit has no subcommands. Dev agent interpreted as deprecation warning + base audit run. Reasonable decision but AC wording needs tightening in future epics.\n    49→- **Dropped subcommands risk** — `onboard epic` and other old subcommands were silently dropped with no deprecation warning (only `onboard scan` got one). May surprise users who relied on those subcommands.\n    50→- **Old exports removal risk** — `onboard.ts` exported shared state getters (`getLastScanResult`, etc.). Dev agent verified no external consumers before removing. Good diligence.\n    51→\n    52→---\n    53→\n    54→## 3. What Went Well\n    55→\n    56→- **Clean refactoring execution.** 478 lines reduced to 40 lines with a well-structured shared handler extraction (`audit-action.ts`). Both `audit` and `onboard` now share identical logic.\n    57→- **Code review caught real bugs.** The unsafe type assertion was a genuine type safety hole. Catching it before merge prevented potential runtime issues.\n    58→- **No regressions.** 2783 tests passing, zero failures across the full suite after the refactor.\n    59→- **Good dependency verification.** Dev agent checked all removed imports to confirm no other consumers before deleting — library files preserved as required.\n    60→- **Story creation quality.** Session issues log captured ambiguities and risks upfront during create-story phase, enabling informed decisions during implementation.\n    61→\n    62→---\n    63→\n    64→## 4. What Went Wrong\n    65→\n    66→- **Test file size underestimated.** Story estimated 100-150 lines for `onboard.test.ts`; actual was 325 lines (needed compaction to 230). Estimates for test files are consistently too low.\n    67→- **Two code quality issues deferred.** `console.log` usage and the no-op `formatAuditJson()` were flagged but not fixed. Both are minor but accumulate as tech debt.\n    68→- **Session ended with story still in verifying.** The full pipeline (create → dev → review → verify) didn't complete within the session window.\n    69→\n    70→---\n    71→\n    72→## 5. Lessons Learned\n    73→\n    74→### Patterns to Repeat\n    75→\n    76→- **Extracting shared handlers** when aliasing commands. The `audit-action.ts` pattern is clean and reusable for future command aliases.\n    77→- **Session issues log as living document.** Each phase (create-story, dev-story, code-review) contributed entries, creating a complete audit trail. This works.\n    78→- **Code review as bug-catching gate.** The unsafe type assertion would have shipped without review. The review phase paid for itself this session.\n    79→\n    80→### Patterns to Avoid\n    81→\n    82→- **Underestimating test file sizes.** Double the estimate when test files involve multiple mock setups and flag combinations.\n    83→- **Ambiguous ACs referencing non-existent features.** \"Maps to equivalent subcommand\" when no subcommand exists forces dev agents to make judgment calls. Be explicit about deprecation behavior in ACs.\n    84→\n    85→---\n    86→\n    87→## 6. Action Items\n    88→\n    89→### Fix Now (Before Next Session)\n    90→\n    91→- [ ] Complete verification pass for Story 3-3-onboard-alias (currently `verifying`)\n    92→\n    93→### Fix Soon (Next Sprint)\n    94→\n    95→- [ ] Add `raw()` output utility to `src/lib/output.ts` for pre-formatted string output that shouldn't be prefixed — resolves the `console.log` tech debt in `audit-action.ts`\n    96→- [ ] Review whether `formatAuditJson()` should do actual formatting or be removed as a no-op\n    97→- [ ] Add deprecation warnings for `onboard coverage`, `onboard audit`, `onboard epic` subcommands (currently silently dropped)\n    98→\n    99→### Backlog (Track but Not Urgent)\n   100→\n   101→- [ ] Improve story estimation heuristics for test file sizes — current estimates consistently 50-100% low\n   102→- [ ] Create AC writing guideline: never reference features/subcommands that don't exist without specifying fallback behavior explicitly\n   103→\n   104→---\n   105→\n   106→# Session Retrospective — 2026-03-21 (continued)\n   107→\n   108→**Timestamp:** ~05:10Z – ~05:40Z\n   109→**Sprint progress:** 17/20 stories done (85%), Epic 3 complete, Epic 4 in progress\n   110→\n   111→---\n   112→\n   113→## 1. Session Summary\n   114→\n   115→| Story | Epic | Outcome | Phases Completed |\n   116→|-------|------|---------|-----------------|\n   117→| 3-3-onboard-alias | Epic 3: Audit Command | Done | verify (completed this window) |\n   118→| 4-1-dockerfile-rules-validation | Epic 4: Infrastructure Guidelines | Verifying | create-story, dev-story, code-review |\n   119→\n   120→Two stories progressed this window. Story 3-3 completed its verification pass — all 8 ACs passed black-box Docker verification, closing Epic 3 entirely. Story 4-1 was created, implemented, and code-reviewed, reaching `verifying` status. It adds Dockerfile validation rules to the infrastructure check pipeline.\n   121→\n   122→**Test results at session end:** 2817 tests passing across 120 files, 96.99% overall coverage, all files above 80% floor.\n   123→\n   124→---\n   125→\n   126→## 2. Issues Analysis\n   127→\n   128→### Bugs Discovered During Implementation\n   129→\n   130→- **Operator precedence ambiguity** (HIGH) — `checkVerificationTools` in dockerfile-rules had `&&`/`||` chains without parentheses, producing incorrect evaluation order. Fixed during code review.\n   131→- **COPY --chown pattern missed** (MEDIUM) — `checkNoSourceCopy` regex only matched plain `COPY` but not `COPY --chown=...` flag patterns. Regex updated during code review.\n   132→- **Redundant double-read of Dockerfile** (MEDIUM) — `checkInfrastructure` read the Dockerfile once for precondition checks, then `validateDockerfile()` read it again. Eliminated the redundant read during review.\n   133→- **Pre-existing test failure** — `run-helpers.test.ts` (`--live` flag test) was broken before this session and had to be fixed before 3-3 verification could proceed. Not caused by this sprint's changes.\n   134→\n   135→### Workarounds Applied (Tech Debt Introduced)\n   136→\n   137→- **Loose tool name matching** (LOW, not fixed) — `checkVerificationTools` uses `content.includes(tool)` which matches tool names anywhere in the Dockerfile, not just in `apt-get`/`apk` install lines. Accepted per story design: \"False positives are acceptable.\"\n   138→- **`checkBinaryOnPath` has no line number** (LOW, not fixed) — Other validation checks report line numbers for failures, but this one does not. Inconsistent output format.\n   139→\n   140→### Code Quality Concerns\n   141→\n   142→- **Branch coverage at 87.5%** for `dfGap()` helper — The `line !== undefined` conditional has one branch not fully covered. Cosmetic; both paths exercised indirectly through integration tests.\n   143→- **Dual purpose of rules markdown** — Story chose hardcoded rules with markdown as reference docs. This means rule updates require code changes, not just doc edits. Reasonable for now but creates maintenance coupling.\n   144→\n   145→### Verification Gaps\n   146→\n   147→- **3-3-onboard-alias:** Observability gaps noted — no structured log events emitted for audit/onboard CLI interactions. Not a regression (was never there), but a gap.\n   148→- **4-1-dockerfile-rules-validation:** Still in `verifying` status at session end.\n   149→\n   150→### Tooling/Infrastructure Problems\n   151→\n   152→- **Pre-existing broken test** blocked verification of 3-3. The `--live` flag test in `run-helpers.test.ts` was unrelated to any current story but had to be fixed to get a clean test run. Time wasted on unrelated fix.\n   153→\n   154→### Planning/Ambiguity Issues\n   155→\n   156→- **Rules as code vs. documentation ambiguity** — Epic 4 story spec was unclear on whether Dockerfile rules should be data-driven (parsed from markdown) or hardcoded. Dev agent chose hardcoded, which is simpler but less flexible.\n   157→- **AC expansion** — Epic defined 4 ACs for 4-1; story creation expanded to 10 ACs to cover each rule category individually. Good granularity but shows epic-level ACs were too coarse.\n   158→\n   159→---\n   160→\n   161→## 3. What Went Well\n   162→\n   163→- **Epic 3 fully completed.** All three stories (3-1, 3-2, 3-3) done and verified. The audit command subsystem is production-ready.\n   164→- **Clean verification for 3-3.** All 8 ACs passed black-box Docker verification on first attempt. No escalations needed.\n   165→- **Code review caught three real bugs in 4-1.** Operator precedence, missed COPY pattern, and redundant I/O — all fixed before merge. Review continues to be the highest-value gate.\n   166→- **Test suite growth healthy.** 34 new tests added (2783 to 2817), one new file added to coverage tracking (119 to 120). No test inflation or flaky additions.\n   167→- **Coverage held steady.** 96.97% to 96.99% — new code matched existing quality bar.\n   168→\n   169→---\n   170→\n   171→## 4. What Went Wrong\n   172→\n   173→- **Pre-existing broken test wasted time.** The `--live` flag test failure in `run-helpers.test.ts` was unrelated to any current work but blocked the verification pipeline. This should have been caught and fixed in a prior session.\n   174→- **4-1 did not complete verification.** Same pattern as first window — the full pipeline (create, dev, review, verify) does not fit in a single session window for non-trivial stories.\n   175→- **Loose matching accepted as \"good enough.\"** The `content.includes(tool)` pattern in `checkVerificationTools` will produce false positives. Deliberately accepted, but adds noise to audit output for users with tool names appearing in comments or other contexts.\n   176→\n   177→---\n   178→\n   179→## 5. Lessons Learned\n   180→\n   181→### Patterns to Repeat\n   182→\n   183→- **AC expansion during story creation.** Going from 4 epic-level ACs to 10 story-level ACs gave clear pass/fail criteria for each validation rule. Verification is straightforward when ACs are granular.\n   184→- **Fixing pre-existing failures immediately.** The `--live` flag test fix during 3-3 verification was a good decision — carrying broken tests forward compounds problems.\n   185→- **Code review as mandatory gate.** Two sessions in a row, code review caught HIGH-severity bugs (type assertion bypass, operator precedence). The gate is paying for itself consistently.\n   186→\n   187→### Patterns to Avoid\n   188→\n   189→- **Letting broken tests accumulate.** The pre-existing `run-helpers.test.ts` failure should have been caught by CI, not discovered during manual verification. If CI is green with a broken test, the CI configuration has a gap.\n   190→- **Accepting loose matching without documenting the known false positive scenarios.** \"False positives are acceptable\" needs a list of known false positives so users understand the tradeoffs.\n   191→\n   192→---\n   193→\n   194→## 6. Action Items\n   195→\n   196→### Fix Now (Before Next Session)\n   197→\n   198→- [ ] Complete verification pass for Story 4-1-dockerfile-rules-validation (currently `verifying`)\n   199→- [x] Complete verification pass for Story 3-3-onboard-alias — done this window\n   200→\n   201→### Fix Soon (Next Sprint)\n   202→\n   203→- [ ] Add line number reporting to `checkBinaryOnPath` for consistency with other Dockerfile checks\n   204→- [ ] Document known false positive scenarios for `checkVerificationTools` loose matching\n   205→- [ ] Investigate why the `--live` flag test in `run-helpers.test.ts` was broken without CI catching it — possible CI gap\n   206→\n   207→### Backlog (Track but Not Urgent)\n   208→\n   209→- [ ] Consider data-driven Dockerfile rules (parsed from markdown) instead of hardcoded — reduces maintenance coupling for rule updates\n   210→- [ ] Add structured log events for audit/onboard CLI interactions (observability gap noted during 3-3 verification)\n   211→- [ ] Improve `dfGap()` branch coverage from 87.5% to 100% — cosmetic but keeps the bar clean\n   212→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_01XEijqg7GKv1ji1qbRnAvz8","session_id":"ef2f2ce5-c013-4ad4-b6dd-a80c40f8ca85","uuid":"94cfa6ca-9fb5-424b-bb8e-fca236356b3c","timestamp":"2026-03-21T05:37:36.556Z"}
